        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>FU Ori has a dust continuum flux density of 66 mJy at 850~\mic\  (350 GHz; Sandell \&amp; Weintraub 2001). We aim to measure  gas emission from the (3-2) transitions of CO and $^{13}$CO, and CS (7-6). The CO (3-2) transition will be less affected by optical depth than the (1-0) or (2-1) transitions and will also be less contaminated by outflows (in any case, FU Ori has no detected outflow in CO (3-2) down to 0.06~K; Evans et al.~1994). The transition is a good tracer of the disk emission ($E_u=33$~K), and also allows to obtain high angular resolution without using the largest ALMA configuration. We also include a CS (7-6) baseband to trace the disk in a different molecule than CO. CS generally traces similar structures to those seen in C$^{18}$O (Yang et al. 1997), and is a good density tracer of warm material (Evans 1999). 

A CO (2-1) observation of FU Ori shows a peak around 5~K, with a total width of about 3~\kms (see Fig.~1), and we can expect similar peaks for the (3-2) transition. For the isotopologues, lines of 1-3~K can be expected (e.g., Evans et al. 1994).  We aim to reach an rms sensitivity of 0.5~K in a bin of 0.25~\kms, i.e., a tenth of the peak temperature for a binsize about a tenth of the total CO (3-2) line width. This goal can be reached with 3.37~h of time on source, i.e., 8.15~h, including calibration and overhead. We plan to use basebands of 100~\kms~ width (0.05~\kms~ resolution). Although the resolution is too high for our needs, we will rebin the spectra to obtain sufficient signal-to-noise ratio per bin. The baseband width is also sufficient to cover the line. We add also two 2 GHz continuum basebands to detect the disk dust emission. 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
